    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "368108a9_7faa11bb",
        "filename": "javatests/org/chromium/distiller/EmbedExtractorTest.java",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 374,
      "author": {
        "id": 1144344
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-15T09:27:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hmm. I guess you are saying with --use-zoom-for-dsf, it is possible that setting 50px doesn\u0027t necessarily get you exactly 50px back through web-platform APIs, since px is no longer a special unit that preserves exact precision. This might be quite unexpected for web developers. Could the rounding difference be amended somehow? Like using the same rounding mode in .width as in .clientWidth.\n\nPreserving the exact width/height value if an integer px number is specified has been taken for granted, even if this is not part of the web spec. The impact of --use-zoom-for-dsf as is might be quite large. For example, all testImageExtractor* tests would need to be changed because none of the dimensions are exact anymore.",
      "parentUuid": "21551486_6bd1f8d7",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 374,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 374,
        "endChar": 47
      },
      "revId": "3d9c82535259c72b54b8d3e0077ea032a6b0f6a6",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2550ba95_8ab194e8",
        "filename": "javatests/org/chromium/distiller/EmbedExtractorTest.java",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 374,
      "author": {
        "id": 1237911
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-02-15T16:09:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, I agree with your concern.\n\nHere is my view on this issue:\nFirst of all, --use-zoom-for-dsf is independent with this precision issue. The motivation of the project (i.e., merging DSF into the page scale factor) is to solve many problems that stems from DSF using the solutions we already have for the page scale factor.\nThis precision issue exists even in the page scale factor. Thus, merging DSF into the page scale factor does not solve it. We need a solution even for the page scale factor. The reason why we did not see any bug from this precision issue is that we have not checked this weird page scale factor (e.g., 2.625 or 3.875) before. Not only this test has a precision problem .. I already met many precision issues from many tests (there are complicated .. we need better design to handle the precision that makes them easy).\n\nIt makes me frustrated that --use-zoom-for-dsf is already enabled as default on Aura, which means there are chances to see this problem, but it is not tested with these special device scale factors (e.g., 2.625 or 3.875). Many existing unit tests failed with those scale factors.\n\nPlease note that this is just my view .. but I do not have enough knowledge on it either. For the fundamental solution, we need better design principles (e.g., conversions to DIP from CSS and to Pix from DIP are reasonable, but the opposite does not make sense except unit tests).\n\nI already told this issue to my manager. Let me discuss this issue with bokan@ and boliu@ more and why don\u0027t we just allow this small error here?",
      "parentUuid": "368108a9_7faa11bb",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 374,
        "startChar": 8,
        "endLine": 374,
        "endChar": 47
      },
      "revId": "3d9c82535259c72b54b8d3e0077ea032a6b0f6a6",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
